{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"fields":{"description":"## What\nOn bug close, auto-draw a best-effort `caused_by` link to the culprit ticket via git-blame, with a `--caused-by <id>` param to augment/override, plus a bug-template blame-hunt advisory. Provenance is an externally verifiable factual claim (blame is checkable), not agent self-assessment, so it is safe to derive/accept — unlike a process self-report.\n\n## Files\n- `src/rebar/metrics/blame.py` — new: single-culprit resolver. Blames the **pre-fix** state — the parent of the fixing commit (`<fixing-commit>~1`) — over the bug's recorded `file_impact`, never post-fix HEAD (which would attribute the fixing commit itself). Resolves the dominant culprit commit and maps it to a ticket via its `rebar-ticket:` trailer. Returns None (no link) on ambiguity: no `file_impact`, multi-commit spread, rename/`--follow` uncertainty, or no resolvable trailer.\n- `src/rebar/_commands/transition_close.py` — best-effort auto-link `caused_by` after the bug is closed. **CRITICAL ordering/guard:** the auto-link runs after `txn.transition_core` has committed the STATUS event, so the bug (the link SOURCE) is already `closed`; `graph._links.add_dependency` rejects links from a closed source (`_links.py:242-247` raises ValueError). The auto-link therefore writes via `graph._links._write_link_event(bug, culprit, \"caused_by\", tracker_dir)` **directly**, bypassing the closed-source and cycle guards — which add nothing for a non-blocking, non-cycle-inducing relation on a closed source. Same direct-writer path is used for the explicit `--caused-by` override applied at close time. Failure to resolve never blocks the close.\n- `src/rebar/_commands/transition.py` — parse `--caused-by <id>`.\n- `docs/user-guide.md` — bug-template blame-hunt advisory.\n- `tests/interfaces/lifecycle/test_caused_by_autoderive.py` — new. **All test bug-closes MUST pass a `--class` value** (a bounded `--class` is REQUIRED on bug close after ticket ed13, which this ticket stacks on top of).\n\n## Approach\nThe culprit commit is an externally verifiable factual claim (blame is checkable), not agent self-assessment, so it is safe to derive/accept — unlike a process self-report. Reuses git blame + the existing `rebar-ticket:` trailer resolution rather than a novel mechanism. Auto-derivation is conservative: it links only on a single dominant culprit resolving to a ticket; ambiguous cases (refactors, moves, multi-commit, no `file_impact`) are left to `--caused-by` or `rebar link ... caused_by`. Best-effort — a failed resolution never blocks close, and the edge is written via `_write_link_event` directly so the closed-source guard does not silently swallow it. Auto-derived edges are `classified`-confidence provenance, never authoritative.\n\n## Tests\n- Integration (real temp git repo + store): a bug whose fix edits lines last changed (pre-fix) by a single commit carrying a `rebar-ticket:` trailer auto-gets a `caused_by` link to that ticket (closing with `--class`); an ambiguous multi-commit blame draws no auto-link; `--caused-by <id>` always sets the link.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `tests/interfaces/lifecycle/test_caused_by_autoderive.py` passes: closing a bug (`--class regression`) over a single-culprit fixture yields a `caused_by` link to the resolved ticket (`rebar show <bug> --output json | jq -e '.links[]|select(.relation==\"caused_by\")'`) — proving the direct-writer path defeats the closed-source guard.\n- [ ] an ambiguous two-commit blame yields no auto `caused_by` link — integration test asserts absence.\n- [ ] `rebar transition <bug> in_progress closed --class regression --caused-by <id>` sets the link regardless of blame — test asserts presence."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784428739559759001,"uuid":"3b1d1443-2afe-4648-b0c0-ddb38c1c58e4"}